      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How the Brisbane Property Market Resumes in January
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The market slows from mid-December to mid-January, then restarts. Here is what 2028 sellers should know about timing a January launch, who is actually buying in those early weeks, and how to ride the campaign into autumn.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Every year, the Brisbane property market goes through the same rhythm. Activity slows meaningfully from mid-December, stays quiet through the first two weeks of January, and then returns progressively through the second half of January before the full autumn market arrives in February and March. Understanding that rhythm is the difference between treating January as a dead zone to avoid and using it as a window where serious, decisive buyers compete against a thin field of listings.</p>

      <p>For sellers considering a launch in early 2028, the question is not whether to sell in January or wait for autumn. It is how to prepare during December, time the launch to catch returning buyers, and position the campaign so that it either closes in late January or rolls seamlessly into the strongest stretch of the year.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why the market slows over the Christmas and New Year break</h2>
      <p>The slowdown is a function of four overlapping factors, not one. Buyers are on holiday and are not attending open homes. Schools are out and families who were active in November have stopped searching until their routine restarts. Agencies scale back campaigning in the last two weeks of December, partly because marketing spend returns less in a quiet market and partly because staff are on leave. Solicitors, conveyancers, and banks operate at reduced capacity through the break, which slows the mechanics of any sale that does occur.</p>

      <p>The result is measurable. New listings drop sharply from mid-December. Auction calendars are effectively paused. Buyer inspection numbers at the few opens that do run are a fraction of November levels. Days on market for properties launched in December often extend well into January before genuine engagement returns, which can negatively affect how the listing is perceived once activity resumes.</p>

      <p>Many sellers respond to this pattern by waiting. The assumption is that the autumn market, traditionally strong in Brisbane's inner east, will deliver the best result. That is often true, but it is not the full picture. The seller who waits for autumn competes with every other seller who made the same decision.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What actually happens in January</h2>
      <p>The first two weeks of January are quiet and should be treated as preparation time, not launch time. Buyer activity is near zero in the first week. The second week begins to stir as people return from holidays, but there is little point in an open home when inspection numbers will be thin.</p>

      <p>From the third week of January, activity returns meaningfully. Buyers who held back over Christmas are back online, many of them having used the break to finalise finance, speak to solicitors, and commit to moving. The first major Saturday of active open homes is typically the last Saturday of January, and that weekend sets the tone for the early autumn market.</p>

      <p>Auction calendars for most Brisbane agencies resume in early February, which means January campaigns usually run as private treaty or as an auction with the auction date set in the first fortnight of February. The practical result is a 3 to 4 week campaign launching in mid-to-late January and culminating in early February, often before the full volume of autumn competition has hit the market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why this window favours the prepared seller</h2>
      <p>A property launching in the third or fourth week of January faces a genuinely thinner field than an equivalent launch in late February. New listings are still restarting, and many sellers who could have launched in January have waited. That scarcity matters, because returning buyers in late January are often the most committed part of the buyer pool.</p>

      <p>Families who need to settle before term 1 starts are on a clock. They have decided to move, have the finance in place, and need to exchange contracts in late January or early February to get the settlement timing right for school enrolment. These buyers are decisive, inspect with intent, and do not waste weekends on properties they are not serious about.</p>

      <p>Relocators with jobs starting in February arrive in Brisbane in the third or fourth week of January, often with a short window to secure a home. They are not tyre kickers. Investors acting on financial planning decisions made over the Christmas break, including those responding to changes in tax or loan structures effective 1 January, are also active in this window and tend to move quickly.</p>

      <p>The combination is unusual. You have a thin pool of listings facing a more decisive-than-average pool of buyers. That is a better match than many sellers realise, and it is why a well-prepared January launch can outperform a late-February launch at the same property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to time a January campaign</h2>
      <p>The essential principle is that all preparation happens in December, not January. Photography, floor plans, listing copy, styling, and any deferred maintenance should be finalised before Christmas. Walking into the new year with a campaign ready to launch, rather than a campaign in progress, is the difference between catching the late-January buyer wave and missing it.</p>

      <p>Go live on realestate.com.au and Domain in the third week of January, not earlier. A listing going live in the first week of January spends two weeks accumulating days on market while nobody is looking, and lands in the same position as a fresh January third-week listing except with a worse days-on-market number. That matters, because buyers filter by days on market and the algorithm surfaces newer listings more prominently.</p>

      <p>Schedule the first open home for the last Saturday in January. Plan the second open for the following Wednesday evening or Saturday, giving the listing two weekends of visibility before deciding whether to call for offers, set an auction date in early-to-mid February, or continue the campaign into the autumn market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pitfalls to avoid</h2>
      <p>The first mistake is launching in the first week of January. Buyer activity is still near zero, the listing accumulates days on market before real demand arrives, and by the time genuine buyers are inspecting, the property looks stale. Wait for the returning buyer wave and launch into it.</p>

      <p>The second mistake is pricing aggressively in a thin market. January comparable sales are limited by low transaction volume, and the few sales that do print through the holiday period are not always representative. Rely on November and December data for pricing benchmarks, not the handful of January results available on the day you launch.</p>

      <p>The third mistake is underestimating presentation. Buyers comparing a small field of listings in January are more discerning, not less, than buyers in a busy market. Quality photography and a professionally styled or at minimum decluttered property matter more when there are fewer listings to compare against. A tired presentation stands out for the wrong reasons.</p>

      <p>The fourth mistake is treating January as a soft launch with low expectations. If the property is ready and the market is receptive, treat the campaign as you would any other, with a clear pricing strategy, a disciplined buyer feedback loop, and a willingness to transact when genuine offers come in rather than holding out for a theoretical autumn price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The relationship with the autumn market</h2>
      <p>If the property does not sell in the January window, the next major opportunity is the autumn market, with peak activity from mid-February through March. A January campaign that transitions smoothly into autumn gives the seller two live buyer waves instead of one, without having to pause, re-photograph, or re-launch.</p>

      <p>The practical management of a rolling campaign matters. By early February, the campaign narrative should shift. Fresh open home scheduling, a reassessment of the price guide based on February comparable sales, and possibly an auction date in the fourth week of February give the listing a second wind without the perception of a failed January launch.</p>

      <p>A late-February launch, by contrast, faces a crowded market with every autumn listing competing for the same buyers. The January-into-autumn approach captures both the thin-market decisive-buyer phase and the high-volume autumn phase, which is a better shape for a campaign than autumn alone.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>January can be a genuine opportunity for a well-prepared seller in Brisbane's inner east. Use December for preparation, treat the first two weeks of January as quiet weeks where nothing is launched, go live in the third week, schedule the first open for the last Saturday of January, and be ready to either close in early February or roll the campaign into the autumn market.</p>

      <p>The sellers who do best in this window are the ones who decided in November and executed on a disciplined preparation schedule through December. The sellers who most often miss the window are the ones who only decided to sell in early January and rushed a campaign to market without the groundwork. A good agent will be honest about which position you are in and what the campaign is likely to achieve.</p>

